'''Carbon fiber testing''' is a material science test involving the testing of all [[carbon fiber]] containing materials. The results for the testing are used to select and design material composites, manufacturing processes and to ensured safety and integrity. Particularly safety-critical carbon fiber parts, such as structural parts in machines, vehicles, aircraft or architectural elements are subject to testing.
==Concepts== Testing sciences classify three main disciplines for material testing that especially apply to carbon fiber materials. Most common are [[:wikt:destruction|destructive]] tests, such as stress, fatigue and micro sectioning tests. There are also methods that allow [[non-destructive testing]] (NDT), so the material can be still be used after testing. Common methods are [[ultrasound|ultrasonic]], [[X-ray]], HF Eddy Current, Radio Wave testing or [[thermography]].<ref>{{cite journal|author=Hodgkinson, J.M. |title=Mechanical Testing of Advanced Fibre Composites|journal=Woodhead Publishing|year=2000|isbn=978-1-85573-312-1}}</ref> Additionally, [[Structural Health Monitoring]] (SHM) methods allow the testing during application.
==Testing methods== Carbon ([[carbon fiber reinforced plastic]] and reinforced polymers) are gaining importance as light-weight material. Particularly safety-critical carbon fiber parts, such as aircraft frames, need to be tested destructively (e.g. stress, fatigue) and non-destructively (e.g. fiber orientation, delamination, bonding).<ref>{{cite journal|author=Erb, T.|title=Methodik zur Bewertung von Fehlern in Strukturbauteilen aus Faser-Kunststoffverbunden im Automobilbau|journal=University of Darmstadt|year=2003}}</ref> Typically, destructive tests are carried out to validate the mechanical properties, whereas [[Nondestructive testing|NDT]] are used to monitor and control the manufacturing process of the CFRP parts.<ref>{{Cite journal|author=Hufenbach, W.|year=2007|title=Textile Composite Construction and Manufacturing Technologies for Leight Weight Construction in Mechanical and Automotive Engineering|volume=SDV - Die Median AG}}</ref> As carbon fiber composites are highly individual in shape and material composition novel NDT are emerging and sought for application.<ref>{{Cite journal|authors=Unnthorsonn, R., Jonsson, M. P., Runarsson, T. P.|year=2004|title=NDT Methods for Evaluating Carbon Fibre Composites|journal=Comptest|volume=Bristol: University of Bristol}}</ref> Applicable technologies are radio wave testing<ref>{{Cite journal|authors=Heuer, H., Schulze, M.|year=2011|title=Eddy Current Testing of Carbon Fiber Materials by High Resolution|journal=International Workshop on SMART MATERIALS, STRUCTURES & NDT in AEROSPACE, Conference NDT, Canada 2011}}</ref> and high frequency [[eddy current testing]],<ref>{{Cite web|authors=JEC Composites, Innovation Award NON DESTRUCTIVE TESTING|year=2013|title=Non-destructive test carbon fiber products (dry fabrics and composites) without coupling media|url=http://www.ndt.org/news.asp?ObjectID=50203}}</ref> [[thermography]], shearography,<ref>{{Cite journal|author=Oster, R. |year=2012|title=Non-destructive testing methodologies on helicopter fiber composite components challenges today and in the future|journal=18th World Conference on Nondestructive Testing|volume=Conference Proceedings|pages=16–20|location=Durban, South Africa}}</ref> air coupled laser ultrasonics, terahertz scanning<ref>{{Cite journal|authors=Lopato, P., Chady, T., Sikora, R.|year=2011|title=Testing of composite materials using advanced NDT methods|journal=COMPEL: the International Jour-nal for Computation and Mathematics in Electrical and Electronic Engineering|volume=30|issue=4|pages=1260–1270|doi=10.1108/03321641111133172}}</ref>
==Typical effects and defects== The specifications for integrity of structurally relevant parts depend on the individual manufacturer. However, typically relevant quality criteria of the texture are fiber orientation, gaps, wrinkles, overlaps, distortion, undulation, uniformity<ref>{{Cite journal|authors=Heuer, H., Schulze, M.|year=2011|title=Eddy Current Testing of Carbon Fiber Materials by High Resolution|journal=International Workshop on SMART MATERIALS, STRUCTURES & NDT in AEROSPACE, Conference NDT, Canada 2011}}</ref> as well as defects in the matrix delamination, inclusion, cracks, curing, void, debonding.<ref>{{Cite journal|authors=Leckey, C. A. C., Parker, F. R.|year=2014|title=NDE and SHM Simulation for CFRP Composites|journal=American Society for Composites Technical Conference; 29th; 8-10 Sept. 2014}}</ref> Furthermore, basis weight or carbon fiber volume content are important properties. Generally, defects and effects in carbon fiber materials are classified according to their location as structural defects (carbon fiber related) and matrix defects (resin related). Carbon fiber related effects are tested with X-ray and high frequency testing methods whereas matrix effects are commonly tested with ultrasonic and thermographic methods.
